{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868909/1930110501/0483.xml":{"full_text":"Page Five\nSTEAM ROLLER\n'-CRASH IS FATAL\nTO BOY OF T\n\u2022Joseph Gradiecki, 7 years old,\n1097 Grove st., died last night of in\njuries suffered Monday when an au\nlomobile crashed into a steam roller\n>n the south side.\nMarie Sundholm, 721 Clarence st.,\nwho was riding in the machine,\nI riving by Michael Cieslak, 3313\nSouth Twelth st., was killed instant\nly-\nCrash Injures Seven.\nTwo cars crashed and seven were\ninjured at Kinnickinnic ave. and\nHvmer st. last night. George Ladds,\n25 years old, 562 Herman st., a\npedestrian, was seriously injured. It\nmay be necessary to amputate both\nlegs.\nLloyd Girard, 26 years old, and\nhis wife, Rose, 27 years old, St.\nFrancis, are in County Emergency\nhospital. Girard, driver of one of\nt he cars, Is being held by police. Ed\nward Czapewski, 30 years old, 215\nNorth Greenfield ave., was driver\nof the other car.\nMany Cut, Bruised.\nThose riding with him who were\ncut and bruised are Larry McDer\nmott, 18 years old; 1241 South\nTwentieth st.; Alice Zelinski, 17\nyears old, 2685 South Thirteenth st.,\nand Margaret Golskl, 1402 South\nSecond st.\nMarian Werdemann, 17 years old,\n3408 South Nevada st., who was\nwith Ladds, suffered a possible\nskull fracture.\nErnest Toepke, 48 years old, 2815\nLisbon ave., was struck by an auto\nmobile at Twelfth and Walnut sts.\ntoday and suffered a fractured right\nankle. He was taken to County\nEmergency hospital.\nAustin Park Folk\nMust Go to Court\nAbout Spur Track\nCourt action will be necessary if\nAustin Park residents are to have\nredress from the extension of a spur\ntrack from the Milwaukee road to\nthe George H. Smith Steel Casting\nCo. plant, according to a ruling by\nthe state rail commission late yes\nterday. Austin Park is a subdivi\nsion south of Oklahoma ave., be\ntween South First st. and' Chase\nave.\nTelevision Plays\nFirst Election Role\nCHICAGO Television delivered\nthe first televised progress of a po\nlitical election yesterday.\nImages of charts showing the\nprogress of the senatorial race were\ntelevised from W9XAP, operated by\nThe Daily News.\nJust 10 years ago the first re\nturns of an important election\nthe selection of Warren Harding as\npresident\u2014were broadcast, from\nKDKA. Pittsburgh.\n4 KILLED OVER\nKENTUCKY VOTE\nLOUISVILLE, Ky. Four dead\nand two wounded were the after\nmath of election day riots in Ken\ntucky.\nBoyd Bingham, Democratic mag\nistrate, shot and killed Hampton\nSmith, and was slain, In turn, offi\ncers said, by Smith\u2019s son, William,\nwho escaped with a wound. The\nshooting occurred on Stinking creek,\nnear Barbourville.\nWard Hatfield was slain at\nPhelps in Pike county. Elias Dotson\nwas arrested in connection with the\nshooting.\nBooger Wright was sought for\nthe wounding of Adam Cotter, a\nformer deputy sheriff, at Elkhorn,\nalso in Pike county, after an elec\ntion quarrel.\nEd Doneghy, Negro, was shot and\nkilled at Danville by Joseph Hay\nden, Democratic election officer.\nCandidate Is Wounded.\nLOGAN, W. Va.\u2014A Republican\ncandidate for local office was\nwounded today by shots fired by a\nDemocratic adherent in an outbreak\nof partisanship.\nEmmet Scraggs, Republican can\ndidate for president of the school\nboard here was shot and wounded\nhere today. Claude Gore was\ncharged with shooting with intent\nto kill as the result of shots fired\ninto Scraggs\u2019 automobile.\nThe Grab Bag\nWho Is this person? For what\noffice did he run? On what ticket?\nWhat were the names of the\nThree Wise Men of the East who\nfollowed the star to the birthplace\nof Jesus?\nWhat are the two large bones\nwhich form the leg called?\nBrain Teaser.\nWhy is a dog biting his tail like\na good manager?\u201d\nCorrectly Speaking.\n\u201cMessers\u201d is the plural of \u201cMr.\u201d\nNever use it without names follow\ning It. Do not say, \u201cWe are wait\ning for Messers.\u201d\nToday\u2019s Anniversary.\nOn this date, in 1783, the Ameri\ncan Revolutionary troops were dis\nbanded.\n(Answers on Want Ad Page).\nThe Labor Movement\nGREEN WARNS\nBOULDER DAM\nNOT YET HIRING\nWASHINGTON\u2014President Green\nof the American Federation of La\nbor, warns workers to keep away\nfrom Boulder Dam as there are no\nprospects of work in the immediate\nfuture.\n\u201cIt will be nearly a year before\na contract can be let for construc\ntion,\u201d said the American Federation\nof Labor executive, who has re\nceived a complete report on every\nphase of this project.\nBids Not Yet Asked.\n\u201cIt is unlikely that bids for con\nstruction of the division tunnel and\nthe dam proper will be called for\nprior to July, next year,\u201d the report\nstates.\n\u201cIt will take considerable time for\nfield surveys and investigations,\ntechincal studies, preparations of\ndesigns and specifications and the\nissuance of advertisements, so that\nit will be nearly a year before con\ntract can be let for construction of\nthe dam.\nNo Workers Needed.\n\u201cIt is necessary to emphasize this\nin order to correct the general im\npression which seems to prevail that\na large construction force is to be\norganized at once.\u201d\nIt is expected that all construc\ntion work will be done by contract,\nand that the larger number of men\nin all grades will be employed di\nrectly by the contractors.\nPackers 9 Prosperity\nContinues Through\nBusiness Depression\nCHICAGO\u2014Large meat packing\ncompanies are not affected by the\nbusiness depression, and it is ex\npected they will equal or exceed\nlast year\u2019s profits.\nStorage stocks are reduced and\nthis has made it possible to hold\nprices. The packers\u2019 prosperity is\nshown in the redemption by Armour\nand Co. of $10,000,600 7% per cent\ngold bonds out of accumulated cash\nthat is not listed as profits.\nWilson and Co. retired $2,500,000\n6 per cent notes five months before\nthey were due.\nThe greatest saving by these cor\n'porations was made in reducing the\nnumber of employes. During the\nfirst six months of this year the\nnumber of employes was below the\ncorresponding period a year ago.\nBeginning in June, last year, the\nnumber of employes dropped stead\nily as against a rise during the cor\nresponding month in 1929.\nJews Denied Jobs\nBecause of Race\nReport Declares\nBy Federated Press.\nNEW YORK\u2014An economic form\nof anti-Semitism which denies em\nployment to Jewish men and wom\nen on no other grounds than that\nof their face and race, is gaining\nground in this country and has al\nready assumed dangerous propor\ntions, says a report submitted to\nthe American Jewish congress by\nits committee on discrimination in\nemployment.\nThe head of the technical place\nment bureau of one of the largest\nagencies In the United States is\nquoted to the effect that the Jew\nnow occupies the position of \u201cmar\nginal worker,\u201d finding jobs when\nlabor is scarce but forced off in fa\nvor of Chri\u00abH\u00abnq when the demand\nfor workers Is normal or sub-nor\nmal.\nTammany \u2018Doles\u2019\nPrecede Election\nBy Federated Press.\nNEW YORK\u2014With the winter of\n1930 threatening to be the worst\nsince 1893, Tammany continues its\nancient function of providing doles\nfor the destitute, as a means of\nmaintaining its enormous nvpstige\nin New York working class sec\ntions.\nA vast steel pier is being outfit\nted at a cost of $111,600 to care\nfor 1,300 homeless nightly while\n2,000 are to be given three days\u2019\nwork a week in city parks at $5.50\na day.\nNews of Tammany\u2019s generosity\nwith the city\u2019s money having\nreached other communities, the\nNew York Junior Board of Trade,\nin alarm, has set up a campaign\nfor the jobless to \u201cstay away from\nNew York.\u201d Tammany doles how\never :r illy distributed only\nto potential voters in the city.\nAir Mail Soon to\nHave New Stickers\nNew air mail stickers, adopted by\nthe postoffice department from a\ndesign by Col. L. H. Brittin of.\nNorthwest Airways, Inc., will soon\nbe supplied to the Milwaukee post\noffice. The new sticker incorporates\nthe official air mall insignia in gold,\nwith the words, Sent by Air Mail.\nfor Coughs\nFoley\u2019s Honey end\nTar Compound, nation\nally known Cough\nSyrup, 55 years a\nhousehold remedy.\nOver 100,000,000 bot\ntles sold. Quick and de\npendable for Coughs,\nAsk for Croup (spasmodic), dry,\nFOLEY\u2019S, tickling throat, trouble-\nFamily Size some night coughs.\nSedative without\nopiates, mildly laxative.\nChildren like it. Moth\ners endorse it, exactly\nsuits Elderly Persons.\nSOLD EVERYWHERE\nLabor Meetings\nTODAY.\nFederated Trades Council of Mil\nwaukee and vicinity, Brisbane hall,\n528 Juneau ave.\nBricklayers, Masons, Marble Ma\nsons\u2019 Protective International Un\nion No. 8, Wisconsin, 298 Fourth\nst., 7:30 p. m.\nMarine Cooks and Stewards\u2019 Un\nion of the Great Lakes, 162 Reed\nst., 2 p. m.\nMotion Picture Projectionists\u2019\nUnion No. 164, Alhambra hall, Wis\nconsin ave. and Fourth st., 11:30\np. m.\nPile Drivers No. 1208, Harmonie\nhall, First ave. and Mineral st., 8\np. m.\nTheatrical Stage Employes No.\n18, Musicians\u2019 hall, 532 Edison st.,\n10 a. m.\nWood Carvers\u2019 Assn., room 305,\nBrisbane hall, 8 p. m.\nTOMORROW.\nAuto Truck Drivers, Teamsters\nand Stablemen No. 347, Moose\nlodge hall, 448 Jeferson st., third\nfloor.\nBookbinders No. 49, Miller\u2019s hall,\nEighth and State sts., 8 p. m.\nCarpenters No. 1053 (Millmen),\nBrisbane hall, 8 p. m.\nElectrical Workers No. 494, Bues\u2019\nhall, 296 West Water st., second\nfloor, 8 p. m.\nFederal Labor Union No. 17710,\nLipp\u2019s hall, Third st. and Highland\nave., 8 p. m.\nGlass Workers\u2019 Union, Local\n1204, Lipp\u2019s hall, Third st. and\nHighland ave.\nMachinists, Local 1052, Lipp's\nhall, Third st. and Highland ave.,\n7:30 p. m.\nLabor Party Has\nHuge Program to\nCut Unemployment\nLONDON\u2014The British Labor\ngovernment has prepared building\nschemes to relieve unemployment\nthat will involve the expenditure\nof $589,730,000.\nThe largest individual items in\nthe program are:\n1. Five-year roads construction\nto cost $157,000,000 on which con\ntracts to the amount of many mil\nlions of dollars have already been\nsigned.\n2. Improvements. to railways,\ndocks, water works and gas works\nthat cost $133,500,000.\n3. Complete reorganization and\nconsolidation of Great Britain\u2019s\nelectric light and electric power\nstations to cost $67,500,000.\n4. Important projects to pro\nmote industrial and economic de\nvelopment in the colonies, to codt\n$34,500,000.\nThese total $392,500,000. Th?\nbalance is made up of innumerable\nmunicipal local improvements and\nextensive housing schemes.\nIf anything is wrong with the\nAmerican family life today, it is\nthat there are too few outward evi\ndences of affection in it.\u2014American\nMagazine.\nvV J/\nX.\nVOLUHTEER X\n\nLei\nVolunteer\nPocahontas\nCoal\nHelp You\nWinter time, with stoves\nand furnaces going right\nmerrily why spoil it\nwith smoke-laden air that\nlays a grimy finger on\neverything that it\ntouches? Burn Volunteer\ncoal it\u2019s smokeless\nand get your neighbors to\nburn it. It\u2019s inexpensive,\ngives wonderful heat and\noffers a pleasing solution\nto the smoke problem\nfrom the last place from\nwhich you\u2019d expect aid\u2014\nthe coal itself. You\u2019ll like\nVolunteer coal.\nGood\nCoke,\nToo\nFor those whose heating\nplants are adaptable to\nburning coke, we offer an\nexceptional value in\nNorth Western Coke,\nHere is a fuel that is clean\nto handle and clean to\nburn. Eliminates smoke,\nsoot and grime and re\nduces the ash nuisance to\na minimum. If you use\ncoke and want a depend\nable product, order North\nWestern Coke.\nAsk Your Dealer\nOr Call\nMarquette 7200\nTHE MILWAUKEE LEADER, WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 5, 1930\nCOURT RULES\nCOMPENSATION\nIS FOR INJURY\nST. PAUL, Minn.\u2014The state su\npreme court made an important\ncompensation ruling when it held\nthat an award can be paid not for\nthe accident, but for personal injury\ncaused by the accident. The deci\nsion was based on the English case\nof Burrell and Sons against Sal\nvage.\nThe court, in discussing the case\nbefore it, held that a series of punc\nture wounds from particles of metal\nthat resulted in the death of the em\nploye does not preclude a compensa\ntion award on the ground that\nPrincess Peggy Frocks,\nAprons and Pajamas\nI\nmarvelous event of threefold importance\noffering scores of charmingly styled\nofZMzlwaukee^ garments, in crisp, new, fast color fabrics.\nMEMBER AMERICAN RETAILERS, INCORPORATED\nf Ai Ji k JeSI OOi. i\n\u201cA NEW ONE IF IT FADES\u201d MB\nThis is one of the sales for which the Boston JnPk\nStore is justly famous. It is a sale which will\nbring hundreds of women down early Thurs-\nday morning. It is a sale which will crowd our 1\ndepartment and flood our Hostess Shopping W\nService with telephone and mail orders...'\nand, indeed, it is a sale which no woman can\nafford to miss.\nMsLwW\nfilm BSn\u00ae\n0. jnA US\nn s, ^S r\nChristmas\nThat\u2019s another good\nfew\nthis sale get dozens yU In\nof these useful, practi- Wp I\ncal garments to lay\naway. How glad you\u2019ll J /i\u00dfbx\nbe to have them later\nwhen you wrap their\ncolorful prints in your ncX iS\nChristmas tissues.\nhim Wi\nHail or Telephone Your Order for Frocks, Chic-on Aprons I\nand Pajamas if You Cannot Come In J\n\u2022\u2014be sure to state color (first and second choice), style number, and please note P 3 *4\nthat only some of the models are to be had in extra sizes. if 1\n1/J .u. wte, v 1 I\n\u2014and These J M J//\nLovely Pajamas\nTuck-in Styles, IBHUdaX i\nWide Trousers J\nare made of the same fast\ncolor, crisp, new fabrics. Be No 11^\nsure to get plenty for the\nfamily and don\u2019t forget Mo Hk\nthat pajamas make mighty J'lim\nnice Christmas gifts. Red.\nNu. ana areen. MfA/\nSizes 34, 36, 38 and 40\nWash Frocks and Lingerie\u2014 ll ^\u2018L*y\nSecond Floor \u2014Center ^*l*^^*,*^*^***** 'T\nAsk for \u201cS&H\u201d Stamps. J J\nCivic Alliance Will\nHear Walter Dunlap\nThe West Allis Civic alliance,\ncomposed of luncheon clubs and ad\nvancement associations, will give a\nbanquet at 6:30 p. m. tomorrow in\nAssumption hall, Sixty-third and\nNational aves. Walter Dunlap will\nspeak. The Rev. J. H. Burbach\nwill give the invocation and John\nF. Baker, president, Milwaukee\nCivic alliance, will address the\nmeeting on what the alliance can\naccomplish.\ndeath can not be traced co any\nparticular wound.\nThe decedent operated a machine\nwhich finished piston castings for\nautomobile engines. He frequently\nreceived puncture wounds from par\nticles of metal which were detached\nfrom the casting and would pick\nthese particles out at hon\\e *with an\nordinary needle. He died from\ntetanus, the testimony showing that\nthe germs entered hi s system\nthrough the puncture wounds.\nEXPERTS URGE\nTOOTHBRUSHES\nFOR INFANTS\nMADISON \u2014A toothbrush for a\nbaby, 1 year old, was recommended\nby medical authorities here today.\nAlthough only the first teeth have\nappeared and the eye teeth will not\nappear for several months later, the\nhealth of the child can be aided by\ntaking care of the teeth at 1 year\nof .age.\n\u201c\u2019When the baby is 1 year old, he\nshould have 12 teeth; and It is\nabout this time he should have his\nfirst tooth brush and his training in\nthe care of his mouth and teeth\nshould begin,\u201d declares the health\nbulletin to mothers issued by the\nstate medical society here today,\n\u201cKeep them just as white and\nshiny as when they first appeared.\nThe child soon becomes accustomed\nto having his teeth brushed after\neach meal, and as he grows, this\nroutine will become a part of his\nlife.\nSt. Mary\u2019s Club\nWill Sing Nov. 11\nSt. Mary\u2019s academy Glee club will\ngive its first public concert in the\nschool auditorium on Armistice day,\nNov. 11. Patriotic songs will be\nfeatured. The grade department of\nthe school will present a program\nof dance and dramatic numbers in\nthe school tonight.\nFacta, Ex-Premier\nOf Italy, Is Dead\nTURIN, Italy\u2014Luigi Facta, for\nmer premier of Italy, died this\nmorning at Pinerolo, in Piedmont.\nHe was 69 years old. Facta was\nREPAIRS\nStoves, Furnaces Boilers\nMILWAUKEE STOVE AND\nFURNACE REPAIR CO\nALSO STOVE DEALERS\u2019 SUPPLY CO.\nNew Address\u20143lo Juneau Ave.\nPhones Marquettes 2907-2908\npremier at the time Benito Musso\nlini led his Fascists in their famous\nmarch on Rome an destablished a\ndictatorship.\nGAS COKE\nA good, low-priced fuel.\nTry It these first cold days, and\nyou will burn It all winter.\nEgg $11.50 per ton\nNut 11.50 per ton\nSmall Nut 9.50 per ton\nWithin first zone\nlimits.\nPhone Daly 6720 for prompt\ndelivery.\nMILWAUKEE GAS\nLIGHT CO.\nPage Five","height":"28881","width":"21336"}}
